Useful Commands for github

1. Create branch from git 

   Using switch: git switch -c <new-branch-name>.
  Using checkout: git checkout -b <new-branch-name
  
2. Switchting to a branch from main

   Modern Command:  git switch <branchname>
   Traditional Command: git checkout <branch-name>  
   
3. Verify the Switch

   git switch
   
4. Cheking git history

   Default Log: Run git log to see a detailed list of all commits 
   Compact Summary: Use git log --oneline to display each commit on a single line for a quick overview.
   Visual Graph: Use git log --graph --oneline --all to see an ASCII representation of your branch and merge history.
   View Specific Commit: Use git show <commit-hash> to see the exact changes (diff) introduced in a particular commit
   By Number: Limit the output to the last n commits using git log -n (e.g., git log -5).
   By File: To see the history of a specific file, use git log -- <file-path>. Add -p to see the actual code changes within those commits.
   By Author: Use git log --author="Name" to filter commits by a specific person.
   By Date: Filter by timeframe using --since and --until (e.g., git log --since="2 weeks ago").
   By Message: Search for specific keywords in commit messages using git log --grep="keyword". [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7]
    
   